{"action":"created","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082/events","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082","id":1516513023,"node_id":"I_kwDOABkWpM5aZCb_","number":48082,"title":"Should there be `@fastmath maximum` etc?","user":{"login":"mcabbott","id":32575566,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjMyNTc1NTY2","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/32575566?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott","html_url":"https://github.com/mcabbott","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/mcabbott/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":4,"created_at":"2023-01-02T15:35:27Z","updated_at":"2023-01-06T04:52:51Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"Because `max` is very careful about signed zeros & NaN, `maximum` is quite slow. Should we make `@fastmath maximum` the way to avoid this, or is there a better way? 

At present you can do `@fastmath reduce(max, x)`, but must supply `init`. A minimal improvement would be to provide this method:
```
MethodError: no method matching reducedim_init(::typeof(identity), ::typeof(Base.FastMath.max_fast), ::Matrix{Float64}, ::Int64)
```
Some quick benchmarks:
```julia
julia> fast_maximum(x::AbstractArray{T}; dims) where {T} = @fastmath reduce(max, x; dims, init = float(T)(-Inf));

julia> let x = randn(Float32, 10, 100)
         @btime maximum($x; dims=1)
         @btime fast_maximum($x; dims=1)
         @btime sum($x; dims=1)  # obviously different result!
       end;
  min 3.151 μs, mean 4.278 μs (4 allocations, 608 bytes)
  min 348.730 ns, mean 1.234 μs (1 allocation, 496 bytes)
  min 347.599 ns, mean 1.245 μs (1 allocation, 496 bytes)

julia> let x = randn(Float32, 1000)
         @btime maximum($x)
         @btime fast_maximum($x; dims=:)
         @btime extrema($x)
       end;
  min 2.667 μs, mean 2.689 μs (0 allocations)
  min 94.243 ns, mean 94.790 ns (0 allocations)
  min 8.111 μs, mean 8.225 μs (0 allocations)
```
The same concerns probably apply to `extrema` too.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082/reactions","total_count":1,"+1":1,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null},"comment":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1373142746","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082#issuecomment-1373142746","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/48082","id":1373142746,"node_id":"IC_kwDOABkWpM5R2H7a","user":{"login":"andrewjradcliffe","id":96091198,"node_id":"U_kgDOBbo8Pg","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/96091198?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe","html_url":"https://github.com/andrewjradcliffe","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2023-01-06T04:52:50Z","updated_at":"2023-01-06T04:52:50Z","author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"Not that it's appropriate for Base, but if one's interest is `mapreduce` on dense numeric arrays, then [my package](https://github.com/andrewjradcliffe/VectorizedReduction.jl) is more/less a drop-in replacement for anything that can be written as a fold (including varargs, multidimensional, etc.).

Of course, autodiff will not work since it's LoopVectorization-based.

My general thinking on folds is that packing as much optimization into Base as possible is desirable. The reduce generics take care to handle quite a few special cases (`missing`, `NaN`, etc.), an approach with which I agree, as the machinery must handle everything thrown at it.
However, where to draw a line?


In any case, a comparison:
```julia
julia> let x = randn(Float32, 10, 100)
           @btime maximum($x; dims=1)
           @btime fast_maximum($x; dims=1)
           @btime sum($x; dims=1)  # obviously different result!
           @btime vvmaximum($x, dims=1)
           @btime extrema($x, dims=1)
           @btime vvextrema($x, dims=1)
       end;

  3.037 μs (4 allocations: 608 bytes)
  689.692 ns (1 allocation: 496 bytes)
  449.164 ns (1 allocation: 496 bytes)
  193.622 ns (1 allocation: 496 bytes)
  4.709 μs (1 allocation: 896 bytes)
  518.063 ns (3 allocations: 1.84 KiB)

julia> let x = randn(Float32, 1000)
           @btime maximum($x)
           @btime fast_maximum($x;dims = :)
           @btime extrema($x)
           @btime vvmaximum($x)
           @btime vvextrema($x)
       end;
  1.521 μs (0 allocations: 0 bytes)
  1.056 μs (0 allocations: 0 bytes)
  5.003 μs (0 allocations: 0 bytes)
  26.746 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)
  39.075 ns (0 allocations: 0 bytes)
```","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1373142746/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

{"action":"created","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418/events","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418","id":1431832393,"node_id":"I_kwDOABkWpM5VWAdJ","number":47418,"title":"Base function request: some","user":{"login":"tecosaur","id":20903656,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjIwOTAzNjU2","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/20903656?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur","html_url":"https://github.com/tecosaur","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/tecosaur/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"closed","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":3,"created_at":"2022-11-01T17:50:05Z","updated_at":"2022-11-02T15:18:37Z","closed_at":"2022-11-02T09:36:29Z","author_association":"NONE","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"I've found myself missing an equivalent to common-lisp's `some` quite a few times. For those unfamiliar it functions like so:

```
(some predicate sequence) -> result
```

where `result` is the first element of `sequence` for which `predicate` returns non-nil (see http://www.lispworks.com/documentation/HyperSpec/Body/f_everyc.htm).

I think a Julia `some(predicate=identity, sequence)` which functions basically as `something(predicate.(sequence)..., Some(nothing))` would complement `any` and the `Some`/`something` family, and be a reasonable addition to Base.

Example:
```julia
julia> some(n -> if iseven(n) n^2 end, [1, 3, 4, 7, 8])
16
```

What does triage think?","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":"completed"},"comment":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1300655624","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418#issuecomment-1300655624","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/47418","id":1300655624,"node_id":"IC_kwDOABkWpM5Nhm4I","user":{"login":"andrewjradcliffe","id":96091198,"node_id":"U_kgDOBbo8Pg","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/96091198?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe","html_url":"https://github.com/andrewjradcliffe","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-11-02T15:18:37Z","updated_at":"2022-11-02T15:18:37Z","author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"This sent me on a tangent... Jakob's approach more robust, but if you'd like a `some` which resembles `any`.

```julia
# Via generators (from Jakob)
some2(f, itr) = first(Iterators.filter(f, itr))
some2(f, x...) = first(Iterators.filter(f, x))

# Copying the `_any` approach
some(f, x...) = _some(f, x)
some(f, itr) = _some(f, itr)
_some(f, itr) = _some_impl(f, itr)
_some(f, itr::NTuple) = _some_impl(f, itr)     # homogeneous tuple
function _some(f, itr::Tuple)                  # heterogeneous tuple
    length(itr) > 32 && return _some_impl(f, itr)
    _some_tuple(f, false, itr...)
end

function _some_impl(f, itr)
    anymissing = false
    for x in itr
        v = f(x)
        if ismissing(v)
            anymissing = true
        elseif v
            return x
        end
    end
    return anymissing ? missing : nothing
end

function _some_tuple(f, anymissing, x, rest...)
    v = f(x)
    if ismissing(v)
        anymissing = true
    elseif v
        return x
    end
    return _some_tuple(f, anymissing, rest...)
end
_some_tuple(f, anymissing) = anymissing ? missing : nothing

