sers/andrewjradcliffe/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-07-04T09:31:09Z","updated_at":"2022-07-04T09:31:09Z","author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"> I agree with @mikmoore on the name's consistency. As the added funtion return `findmin(), findmax()` rather than `extrema(), indexes`. Although `findminmax!` has been used for a internal method, we can rename it without breakage.

I went with `findextrema` as per the link in the OP, but perhaps opinions have changed since 2019. Whichever name we choose, we will most likely be stuck with.
My thoughts on name choice are: at first glance, `findminmax` seems most natural, as it confers the notion of `find_min_and_max`.  Alas, `minmax` looks quite similar to `minimax`, which is an entirely different concept. Alternatively, `findextrema`, while arguably uglier, is unambiguous in relation to `extrema`.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1173585309/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

{"action":"created","issue":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/45565","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia","labels_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/45565/labels{/name}","comments_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/45565/comments","events_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/45565/events","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/45565","id":1258941698,"node_id":"PR_kwDOABkWpM45BD65","number":45565,"title":"[RFC] Use mapslices instead of mapreduce for all/any","user":{"login":"LilithHafner","id":60898866,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjYwODk4ODY2","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/60898866?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner","html_url":"https://github.com/LilithHafner","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/LilithHafner/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"labels":[],"state":"open","locked":false,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":6,"created_at":"2022-06-02T23:15:14Z","updated_at":"2022-06-18T23:53:54Z","closed_at":null,"author_association":"MEMBER","active_lock_reason":null,"draft":false,"pull_request":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/pulls/45565","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/45565","diff_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/45565.diff","patch_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/45565.patch","merged_at":null},"body":"fixes #45562 ","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/45565/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/45565/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null,"state_reason":null},"comment":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1159584101","html_url":"https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/45565#issuecomment-1159584101","issue_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/45565","id":1159584101,"node_id":"IC_kwDOABkWpM5FHdll","user":{"login":"andrewjradcliffe","id":96091198,"node_id":"U_kgDOBbo8Pg","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/96091198?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe","html_url":"https://github.com/andrewjradcliffe","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/andrewjradcliffe/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-06-18T23:53:54Z","updated_at":"2022-06-18T23:53:54Z","author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"> Seeking input: what are people's values with respect to the behavior and performance of `all`/`any` in the multidimensional case? Do folks have implementation ideas?

The [current implementation](https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/blob/ae89f8b00a6e785832e4f47de73599e032aa9674/base/reducedim.jl#L286) is such that cost scales only with the size of the array, and is independent of the dimensions being reduced over. Short-circuit in the multidimensional case necessitates an iteration from start to finish over an entire slice, but this can suffer (perhaps quite severely) from non-contiguous memory access patterns. Frequently, such access patterns mean SIMD is also out of the question. The current implementation sacrifices short-circuiting for optimal traversal order and also a very real chance of SIMD (assuming that `op` is amenable, which it is for `&` and `|` -- `f` must also be amenable, but let's assume that it is, for the moment). For example,
```julia
A = rand(1000,1000,10);
# if memory traversal were not consecutive, each iteration would jump 1000*1000 elements.
@btime any(≥(0.5), $A, dims=3)                                                    # 4.862 ms (7 allocations: 976.80 KiB)
@btime [any(≥(0.5), view($A, :, :, i)) for i in axes($A,3)]                       # 68.008 ns (1 allocation: 64 bytes)
# rare events
@btime any(≥(0.999999), $A, dims=3);                                              # 4.863 ms (7 allocations: 976.80 KiB)
@btime [any(≥(0.999999), view($A, :, :, i)) for i in axes($A,3)]                  # 5.888 ms (1 allocation: 64 bytes)
```

From this perspective, the correct algorithm depends on the nature of the problem, as I sketch out [here](https://github.com/andrewjradcliffe/VectorizedReduction.jl#when-to-consider-replacing-anyall-with-vectorized-versions). Assuming an unordered input, this means that unless the event is rare (relative to input size), short-circuiting is less expensive. Alas, that analysis considers only the cost of evaluation, with absolutely no accounting for cost of memory access pattern, the latter of which can be considerable.

None of this is to say that the proposed fix is not admirable, but that it is a difficult problem, and the `Base` implementation is perhaps the best compromise, given that nothing can be assumed about input size and event probability.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/1159584101/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

